## Task: task-004
Implement: C:\Users\ogace\CodexManager\CodexManager\src\Components\InputDialog.tsx

### What To Do
Create a new unified `InputDialog` component that replaces both `EditPasswordDialog` and `EmailLinkDialog`. These two existing components are structurally identical (same state, same refs, same layout, same buttons) but differ in props and one behavioral detail.

### Component Interface
```tsx
interface Props {
  Title: string;
  Description: React.ReactNode;
  InputType: string;
  Placeholder: string;
  InitialValue?: string;
  OnSave: (Value: string) => void;
  OnClose: () => void;
}

export function InputDialog({ Title, Description, InputType, Placeholder, InitialValue, OnSave, OnClose }: Props): JSX.Element
```

### CRITICAL BEHAVIORAL NOTE
The `OnSave` callback must pass the **raw untrimmed** value. This is intentional:
- Passwords may have leading/trailing spaces that must be preserved
- The old `EditPasswordDialog` passed `OnSave(Value)` (untrimmed)
- The old `EmailLinkDialog` passed `OnSave(Value.trim())` (trimmed)
- The unified component does NOT trim. The caller (`App.tsx`, updated in batch 4) will trim when appropriate.

### Implementation Pattern
Follow the exact same UI structure as the existing dialogs. Here is `EditPasswordDialog.tsx` for reference:
```tsx
import { useState, useRef, useEffect } from "react";

export function EditPasswordDialog({ Email, OnSave, OnClose }: Props) {
  const [Value, SetValue] = useState("");
  const InputRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    InputRef.current?.focus();
  }, []);

  const HandleSubmit = (E: React.FormEvent) => {
    E.preventDefault();
    if (Value.trim()) OnSave(Value);
  };

  return (
    <div className="ModalOverlay" onClick={OnClose}>
      <form
        className="Modal"
        onClick={(E) => E.stopPropagation()}
        onSubmit={HandleSubmit}
      >
        <h3 className="Modal__Title">Set Password</h3>
        <p className="Modal__Desc">
          Enter the password for <strong>{Email}</strong>. It will be stored securely.
        </p>
        <input
          ref={InputRef}
          className="Modal__Input"
          type="password"
          placeholder="Enter password..."
          value={Value}
          onChange={(E) => SetValue(E.target.value)}
          autoComplete="off"
        />
        <div className="Modal__Actions">
          <button type="button" className="Btn Btn--Ghost" onClick={OnClose}>Cancel</button>
          <button type="submit" className="Btn Btn--Primary" disabled={!Value.trim()}>Save</button>
        </div>
      </form>
    </div>
  );
}
```

